/public/images/107573fb-0c28-4cea-82f4-5277309153a7_915x355.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:355,&quot;width&quot;:915,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:688,&quot;bytes&quot;:73365,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F107573fb-0c28-4cea-82f4-5277309153a7_915x355.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F107573fb-0c28-4cea-82f4-5277309153a7_915x355.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F107573fb-0c28-4cea-82f4-5277309153a7_915x355.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F107573fb-0c28-4cea-82f4-5277309153a7_915x355.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>我认为我们不必利用桥梁灾难来促进阴谋论或政治仇恨，而是要为未来绘制两个重要的课程。</p><p>首先，美国基础设施比许多人意识到的要脆弱。最近，安全服务一直在引起有关<a href="https://www.wsj.com/politics/national-security/fbi-director-says-china-cyberattacks-on-u-s-infrastructure-now-at-unprecedented-scale-c8de5983">针对美国关键基础设施的中国黑客的</a>警报：</p><blockquote><p>克里斯托弗·雷（Christopher Wray）周日表示，北京为掩盖美国关键基础设施网络中秘密植物攻击恶意软件的努力现在“比我们以前所看到的更大”，他认为这是一个定义的国家安全威胁的问题。</p><p> Wray援引<a href="https://www.wsj.com/politics/national-security/u-s-disables-chinese-hacking-operation-that-targeted-critical-infrastructure-184bb407">台风伏特台化</a>的名字，该名称去年在美国关键基础设施内部处于休眠状态时，他说，北京支持的演员是预位恶意软件，这些恶意软件随时可以触发，以破坏美国关键的基础设施。</p><p>他说：“这是冰山一角……这是中国人的许多​​这样的努力之一。”</p></blockquote><p>这是合理的恐怖。如今，美国的所有内容都已建立联系，几乎所有内容都使用了某种中国制造的电子组件。中国也是世界上大部分的船只。很容易想象在中国袭击台湾的那一天发生的那一天，弗朗西斯·斯科特·钥匙桥的崩溃发生了数十个甚至数百种灾难。因此，我们应该尽力使我们的网络基础架构和身体基础设施都做好准备。</p><p>其次，重建弗朗西斯·斯科特（Francis Scott Key Bridge）的努力将告诉我们很多有关美国国家能力的信息。拜登总统已<a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/fbi-baltimore-bridge-collapse/">承诺财政援助</a>，但这并不意味着维修将按时或便宜地进行。最近在费城的I-95倒塌部分的<a href="https://ifp.org/can-i-95s-repairs-teach-us-to-build-faster/">迅速修复</a>表明，美国的某些地区仍然具有很高的国家能力。桥梁倒塌将测试巴尔的摩的。整个国家（和世界）将关注。</p><h4> 2. Daniel Kahneman，RIP</h4><p>丹尼尔·卡尼曼（Daniel Kahneman）刚刚<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/obituaries/2024/03/27/daniel-kahneman-dead/">去世，享年90岁</a>。尽管他是一名认知心理学家，但他以行为经济学的父亲而闻名，<a href="https://www.nobelprize.org/uploads/2018/06/advanced-economicsciences2002-1.pdf">他在2002年赢得了诺贝尔奖</a>。</p><p>卡尼曼（Kahneman）在1970年代和1980年代进行了开创性的经济研究。当时，经济学家确实认真对待个人理性。他们在模型中认为超理性的“代理”不仅是方便的数学近似值，而且是对实际人类行为的描述。因此，当心理学家出现并开始表明人类实际上<em>并没有</em>像那些模型中的特工那样行事时，这是对整个经济学学科的基础的巨大震惊。</p><p>卡尼曼基本上做了一堆心理学实验，以表明人类的概率不好。他和他的长期合着者阿莫斯·特弗斯基（Amos Tversky）（在他可以分享诺贝尔之前就去世了）<a href="https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1972-01934-001">表明</a>，人们从很小的样本中做出了强烈的推论 - 例如，如果您遇到了来自澳大利亚的两个好人，您可能会得出结论，澳大利亚人一般都很好。卡尼曼将其称为“少数法律”。</p><p>这只是一个更普遍的谬论家族的一个例子，称为<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representativeness_heuristic">“代表性”谬论</a>，Kahneman的实验深入了。另一个著名的例子是图案匹配 - 如果数学教授倾向于戴眼镜，并且您必须猜测某人是基于戴眼镜的数学教授还是服务员，那么您可能会猜测他们是教授。但是，服务员比教授多得多，所以您的猜测是一个糟糕的猜测 - 您犯了<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_rate_fallacy">基本利率忽略</a>的统计罪。</p><p>我可以继续列出示例，但您明白了。卡尼曼发现了许多常见的人类错误。到他完成的时候，毫无疑问，人类并不像1970年代的模型的<em>同性恋者</em>。当然，有例外 - 在线拍卖中竞标Google广告的公司往往采取合理的行为。但是在卡尼曼之后，经济学家始终必须接受行为偏见可能会在预测和经验数据之间引起楔子的可能性。</p><p>这种理解有助于推动经验经济学的兴起，这是过去三十年来<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-08-02/how-economics-went-from-philosophy-to-science">经济领域的巨大变化</a>。 There are many other reasons that econ theories need to be checked against data, but economists had put so much emphasis on rationality that a demonstration of persistent, general, predictable <em>irrationality</em> was an especially effective method of forcing them to think about empirics.</p><p> Ideally, though, we&#39;d want behavioral economics to give us more than just a list of anomalies. If humans are predictably irrational, we should be able to come up with a theory that describes their irrationality. Kahneman came up with <em>psychological</em> theories, about where irrationality comes from in the human mind — you can read about these in his book, <em><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Thinking-Fast-Slow-Daniel-Kahneman/dp/0374533555">Thinking Fast and Slow</a></em> . But he also came up with an economic theory, describing how irrationality affects decision-making. This was called <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prospect_theory">prospect theory</a> .</p><p> Prospect theory is basically a combination of two behavioral biases — loss aversion and overestimation of small probabilities. Laboratory evidence <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41562-020-0886-x">generally supports prospect theory</a> , but applying it in the real world has <a href="https://pubs.aeaweb.org/doi/pdfplus/10.1257/jep.27.1.173">proven to be very tough</a> , for one big reason — it&#39;s hard to know what counts as a <em>loss</em> in people&#39;s minds. Do people measure gains and losses relative to what they had yesterday, what they had a year ago, or what they expected to have? It&#39;s hard to predict.</p><p> But even though he didn&#39;t manage to completely replace existing econ theory, Kahneman&#39;s towering influence over the economics field is undeniable. He was an all-too-rare example of a social science researcher who can cross disciplinary boundaries and apply insights from one field to transform another.</p><h4> 3. Joe Biden supports nuclear power</h4><p> Nuclear power is <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/solar-is-happening-nuclear-is-mostly">not going to be our main source</a> of green energy.那将是太阳能（带有用于存储的电池）。 But nuclear is still important! First of all, we already have a bunch of nuclear plants already built; shutting them down, as <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/nuclear-reactors-germany-invest-gas-power-plants-energy/">Germany</a> and <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2024/mar/20/nuclear-plant-closure-carbon-emissions-new-york">New York</a> did, and as California is now <a href="https://www.latimes.com/environment/story/2023-12-14/california-energy-officials-vote-to-extend-diablo-canyon-operations#:~:text=Gavin%20Newsom%20supports%20keeping%20the,planned%20shutdown%20date%20of%202025.&amp;text=California%20energy%20officials%20have%20voted,plant%20an%20additional%20five%20years.">threatening to do</a> , is absolute madness in the face of the climate crisis. And nuclear is a helpful source of “clean firm” power to replace that last bit of natural gas.环保组织反对核电是愚蠢的。</p><p> Meanwhile, every President, Democrat or Republican, pays lip service to nuclear power and then does little to support it. Trump did commit a bit of money to nuclear energy <em>research</em> , but not much to support the existing industry.</p><p> But Joe Biden and his administration are pragmatic and sensible. They are industrialists first and foremost. So Biden is actually <a href="https://www.energy.gov/articles/biden-harris-administration-announces-15-billion-conditional-commitment-holtec-palisades">doing something real and tangible</a> to support nuclear power:</p><blockquote><p> As part of President Biden&#39;s Investing in America <a href="https://gcc01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Flink.mediaoutreach.meltwater.com%2Fls%2Fclick%3Fupn%3Du001.SyN0b0LCQryBI5pjHay1iIgo9cBdzV9vne5ipBzFwmU90eyVW5LML4Z06DvE-2Fck9Czhysbl0C6u4-2BrV9EDRfE62xO3-2BQ-2B4Apd4Ma3L5EQ2k-3DpISf_4-2BCeSnTfNElQaOz0iIYXcdu3gNm0KCJmsrndKdbUMaPaXXbz5gfKAZRK0oB8JQT2QfawfUCgM7audm8nv1iWep74gKBwW-2BXeNyeiAxhYgx-2FTExhef5-2FqC5x5PqyiBqa3nGl-2B1BrUsz6kfgcdT2HKZAPYhCuhzbyhGjs9sorXxaVL4reie70PEwv-2BF6JqXlOjnjEG3haRCufmi6Ziupkb-2B8rPOXZhL1CrkI1nBkgQkJ3XGx56JeySlfIUA5EMu01PFJYlZnrbAZmTo0-2Fqr46rKFip0qm5PlpEzejjajRVsa6maH5l70Qhp-2BGcRIPeGwdDnvokXasAynYF5abFBemc9feZDY9v1xFYi1km1VtNXXzB-2BjOOVi0FC4Pl8peYgz1O&amp;data=05%7C02%7Clucy.vernasco%40hq.doe.gov%7C601394c1d9a04557317008dc4ce5289c%7C6b183ecc4b554ed5b3f87f64be1c4138%7C0%7C0%7C638469794309024774%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C0%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=82LH5vc9SlLZjpTNgjyXnIKDIZxc%2B2NBDT6FpVkDVsA%3D&amp;reserved=0">agenda</a> , the US Department of Energy (DOE) through its Loan Programs Office (LPO) today announced the offer of a conditional commitment of up to $1.52 billion for a loan guarantee to Holtec Palisades to <strong>finance the restoration and resumption of service of an 800-MW electric nuclear generating station in Covert Township, Michigan</strong> . The project aims to <strong>bring back online the Palisades Nuclear Plant</strong> , which ceased operations in May 2022, and upgrade it to produce baseload clean power <strong>until at least 2051</strong> …</p><p> “ <strong>Nuclear power is our single largest source of carbon free electricity</strong> , directly supporting 100,000 jobs across the country and hundreds of thousands more indirectly,” said US Secretary of Energy Jennifer M. Granholm. “President Biden&#39;s Investing in America agenda is supporting and expanding this vibrant clean energy workforce here in Michigan with significant funding for the Holtec Palisades nuclear power plant.&quot; (emphasis mine)</p></blockquote><p> If you are a supporter of nuclear power, you should give Biden credit for this.</p><p> Now, it&#39;s not year clear if this is a one-off measure, or a sign of a general turn by the administration toward supporting nuclear plants across America. Nor is it clear whether the administration will be willing and able to push through permitting reform, which is necessary for building nuclear as well as solar. But this is an important start. And if you&#39;re a nuclear advocate, you should give credit where credit is due, in order to encourage more of the same.</p><h4> 4. Small signs of the ebbing of unrest?</h4><p> I <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/calling-the-top-on-our-age-of-unrest">called the top on America&#39;s age of unrest</a> pretty early — all the way back in mid-2021. Since then, I think events have <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-new-1970s">broadly been consistent</a> with that call, though of course a disputed election or the election of Trump could upend things later this year. But anyway, I continue to see small signs that unrest is beginning to subside just a little bit.</p><p> For example, people are looking at news websites a lot less than in February 2020 (which was before the pandemic had fully struck). And traffic to right-wing websites, both fringe and mainstream, is <a href="https://www.therighting.com/election-year-audience-erosion-continues-for-right-wing-websites">down by even more</a> : </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F9e05e4d3-7a3b-4595-874a-7677dd63f8a9_798x713.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F